  <section class="section" id="work">
    <span class="section-tag">Where the work is going</span>
    <h2>Three realities at the same time.</h2>

    <div class="bento">
      <div class="card c2 reveal">
        <span class="card-icon">1</span>
        <div class="card-title">More plugins can be nudged forward</div>
        <p class="card-body">
          Legacy scheduler calls and common Paper or Bukkit assumptions can sometimes be bridged into region-threaded behavior
          without lying about ownership or safety.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card c2 reveal" style="transition-delay:.05s">
        <span class="card-icon">2</span>
        <div class="card-title">Some plugins need to be blocked</div>
        <p class="card-body">
          If a plugin reads or mutates world state from the wrong execution context, the right answer is often a clean disable
          with a readable log message, not pretending it is fine.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card c2 reveal" style="transition-delay:.1s">
        <span class="card-icon">3</span>
        <div class="card-title">Vanilla behavior still matters</div>
        <p class="card-body">
          Redstone, combat, inventories, chunk loading, commands, networking, AI, scoreboards, and world generation are not
          optional collateral damage for plugin compatibility experiments.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card c3 reveal" style="transition-delay:.14s">
        <div class="card-title">What SilkMC is actively trying to improve</div>
        <p class="card-body">
          Scheduler compatibility, legacy synchronous task assumptions, event consistency, thread ownership handling,
          async plugin behavior mitigation, and safer region-thread bridging.
        </p>
        <span class="card-chip">narrow the gap</span>
      </div>

      <div class="card c3 reveal" style="transition-delay:.18s">
        <div class="card-title">What SilkMC is intentionally avoiding</div>
        <p class="card-body">
          Unsafe “just make it work” hacks that hide region violations, make upstream merges painful, or quietly trade plugin convenience
          for corruption risk and impossible debugging later.
        </p>
        <span class="card-chip blue">correctness over illusions</span>
      </div>
    </div>
